Flat Tax Lite
nytimes_articles.abstract:
The flat tax has emerged as the central issue in the Republican Presidential  primaries. The debate now pits an ideal, pure flat tax proposed by Steve Forbes  against modified plans proposed by Phil Gramm and Patrick J. Buchanan that retain popular deductions like home mortgage interest and charitable contributions. 

     Advocates for a modified flat tax are worried that, under the unadulterated plan, housing values, home ownership and charitable giving would fall. But these dire predictions are unfounded. Under the current graduated rate system, the deductions for mortgage interest and charitable giving favor people in high tax  brackets. Currently, the Treasury allows someone with a million-dollar mortgage  to deduct the interest and receive a refund exceeding $70,000, while someone with a smaller mortgage gets a refund of a few thousand dollars.

O.J. Simpson, Under Oath
nytimes_articles.abstract:
For the first time, O. J. Simpson has spoken under oath about the deaths of Nicole Simpson and Ronald L. Goldman. Though the proceedings will not begin until April, Mr. Simpson began giving his deposition yesterday in the wrongful-death lawsuit brought by the victims' families. 

     In the long criminal trial against Mr. Simpson, it sometimes seemed as though the case was about everything but the fundamental question -- whether the defendant murdered two people. But the civil trial against Mr. Simpson promises  to look very different, and not just because the burden of proof is less onerous. For one thing, we'll most certainly hear Mr. Simpson's version of events -- which seemed as if it was the only version of events missing from the  criminal trial.

The Palestinian voice has been muffled since the beginning of the Arab-Jewish conflict, and for more than 100 years the Palestinians have never been given the right to speak out for themselves. Their national identity has been negotiated between different parties to the conflict and rendered a moot question at best.

During a bitter exchange on the Senate floor in April 1850, Henry Foote of Mississippi drew a pistol and advanced on Thomas Hart Benton of Missouri. Senator Benton stood up, allegedly pulled open his shirt and cried out, "Let the assassin fire!" Cooler heads wrestled the gun from Senator Foote's hands and order was restored. 

     Clearly, Congress can be a tough place. Incidents of extreme behavior -- though, thankfully, not this extreme -- have taken place at moments of tension and change throughout American history. So the next time a moderate Congressman  calls it quits, complaining about the "unprecedented" incivility, frustration and polarized extremes on Capitol Hill today, we can take comfort in the historical record: it has always been like this, and this too shall pass. But has it and will it?

wiki_events.headline: Billy Bailey becomes the last person to be hanged in the United States.

pages.title: Billy Bailey
pages.description: American convicted murderer; last person to be hanged in the US
pages.abstract: Billy Bailey was a convicted murderer who was hanged in Delaware in 1996. He became the third person to be hanged in the United States since 1965, and the first person hanged in Delaware in 50 years. As of 2026, he remains the last person to be lawfully executed by hanging in the United States.
